@@ -74,7 +74,7 @@ ## 4. Building and booting a GNOME OS image
 
 > If you're already running GNOME OS (e.g. if you installed it by using the [prebuilt images](https://os.gnome.org/)) and want to deploy your changes to it directly, you can skip this step and jump directly to the [Making changes](#6-making-changes) section instead
 
-The first build might take a while depending on your workstation's specs and which secure boot key configuration you've set up earlier.
+The first build might take a while depending on your workstation's specs and which secure boot key configuration you've set up earlier. On a 2025 workstation with a fast SSD, 32 GB of RAM, 24 cores, and a 1 Gb/s internet connection, the first build with the `snakeoil` keys takes about 25 minutes and requires about 50 GB of disk space. Subsequent rebuilds are much faster and take about one minute from making a change to seeing the change running on the workstation.
 
 ### 4.1 Option 1: In a virtual machine
 
@@ -145,7 +145,7 @@     strict: false
 EOT
 ```
 
-Here, `strict: false` avoids rebuilding the whole chain on the next build, and `override-project-caches: true` disables remote cache lookups which, while helpful on the first build, can significantly slow down things on subsequent builds.
+Here, `strict: false` avoids rebuilding the whole chain on the next build, and `override-project-caches: true` disables remote cache lookups which, while helpful on the first build, can significantly slow down things on subsequent builds. By default, the cache is stored in `~/.cache/buildstream`. Note disabling the remote cache lookups will cause a slow fresh build from scratch without the caches the first time you run a `bst` command afterwards.
 
